In article <1993Feb25.141347.19406@serval.net.wsu.edu>, dhanlen@beta.tricity.wsu.edu (Don A. Hanlen) writes:
|> The following shuffle algorithm bothered me:
|> 
|> >A correct version of step 3 for the 52-card case is:
|> >
|> >3. for n := 52 downto 2
|> >	 generate a random integer 'r' in the range 1..n 
|> >	 swap array[r] <-> array[n]

   .  .  .

|> Let me ask, what is the probability that the card at the top of the deck
|> (#52), will be at the top at the end of the shuffle?
|> 
|> Answer:  0 (!)

Not true.

Remember that 1<=r<=n, so there is a 1/n probability of r = n, resulting
in a swap of array[n] with array[n], e.g., no change in position.  This
is a proper shuffle.
